posts.cooked: Our team is currently using the code of 6328 for our swerve. We are evaluating whether to switch to CTRE Cross The Road Electronics and would like to know the advantages and disadvantages of doing so.

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked:
When you mention "the code of 6328," are you referring to the AdvantageKit TalonFX swerve template? The AdvantageKit templates are designed to ensure compatibility with log replay in simulation, unlike CTRE's Cross The Road Electronics (CRORE) code, which lacks such compatibility without significant tradeoffs. The key distinction lies in their approaches to logging.

If log replay isn't important—only normal logging matters—the AdvantageKit templates may not be suitable. However, CRORE's swerve code could be a better fit under these circumstances, provided supported hardware is available. Conversely, if log replay is a priority, the AdvantageKit templates are likely the best choice.

posts.name: Carter Ryba
posts.cooked: To add onto this, we used the tunerx generated code for about 2 days before switching to the advantagekit code. We got significantly better performance from the advantagekit template than anything else.
CTR added some sort of log replay functionality this year, and Phoenix 6 will soon be released with New for 2025

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked: Despite a confusing choice of name, Hoot Replay has significantly different functionality from AdvantageKit and deterministic log replay.

link_counts.title: Comparison of Log Replay Tools | AdvantageKit

posts.name: Tim Winters
posts.cooked: What metrics are you using to compare performance?

posts.name: Carter Ryba
posts.cooked: Ability to understand, ease of debugging, things on that kinda level. I suppose performance wouldn't necessarily be the right word.

posts.name: Dalton
posts.cooked: Do you have any specific pain points that we can improve upon?

posts.name: Carter Ryba
posts.cooked:
No, honestly, both software and hardware-wise, everything we did with C-TRE worked seamlessly. In fact, we wouldn’t have gotten our robot running without the TunerX Swerve Generator. I prefer the Akit template now, especially since this is my first year on our team and also my second year programming in Java. I found it more intuitive because the way it’s designed makes more sense to me as a novice programmer.

In simpler terms, continue what we’re currently doing because our experience with C-TRE was exceptionally smooth—everything went without a hitch.
It's important for us to keep the simulation and log abilities.

posts.name: Jonah Bonner
posts.cooked:
All common swerve templateslibraries such as AdvantageKitCTRE and YAGSLsupport simulation and logging AdvantageScope lets you view logged data during simulation Regardless of the chosen option The AdvantageKit templates differ by supporting deterministic log replay enabling log files to be replayed directly into robot code during simulation This advanced logging feature aids niche debugging tasks beyond regular capabilities but needs expertise to utilize effectively

When using the AdvantageKit template project could you achieve your requirements solely through AdvantageScope's log viewing If not consider leveraging its advanced replay features which allow additional data logging by replaying logs into the simulation environment Referencing documentation here provides an example
